Table 1
 shows the specific surface area, pore size, and pore volume of Cu-MOF, GO, NGO, and Cu-MOF/NGO. The BET surface area of GO is decreased after doping with nitrogen from 11.57 to 7.07 m2/g. The Cu-MOF has shown the highest BET surface area (724.85 m2/g), and a decrease in surface area was observed after incorporating NGO. However, upon the incorporation of NGO into Cu-MOF, there was a decline in the surface area of Cu-MOF/NGO (446.55 m2/g), confirming the interaction with NGO, which also resulted in decreased pore volume. Furthermore, after adding NGO to Cu-MOF, the BET pore size of Cu-MOF/NGO (2.76 nm) increased slightly. This could be due to increasing the internal pore strain of the composite material. According to the IUPAC classification, type IV (a) with a hysteresis loop of H2 was observed, which is an indication of mesoporous materials (Fig. 3
) [46].
